<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFBEBA4DFF3DFA4DFDDCEFF1" blockId="46.[151,759,1431,1491]" box="[151,561,1466,1491]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFBEBA4DFF3DFA4DFEBAEFF1" bold="true" box="[151,343,1466,1491]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Common name:</emphasis>
Baluchistan gerbil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="039B6556FFBEBA4DFF3DF9F5FE6CEDCD" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFBEBA4DFF3DF9F5FDF6ECD0" blockId="46.[151,1437,1538,2031]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFBEBA4DFF3DF9F5FEE7EC39" bold="true" box="[151,266,1538,1563]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: This is a small-sized gerbil with soles of feet predominantly naked except for some hair on the metatarsals. Back color is sandy buff slightly grayish (
<figureCitation id="D3BA2A58FFBEBA4DFCBFF9D1FC67EC1D" box="[789,906,1574,1599]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="45.[151,250,890,912]" captionTargetBox="[276,1294,193,871]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[276,1294,193,871]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 50. Baluchistan gerbil, Gerbillus nanus (photo by Mohammad Abu Baker)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202875/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Figure 50</figureCitation>
). Tail is distinctly discolored, lacking a welldeveloped terminal tuft (less developed than in 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFBEBA4DFD0DF9BCFCC7EC41" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[679,810,1610,1635]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dasyurus">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFBEBA4DFD0DF9BCFCC7EC41" box="[679,810,1610,1635]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">G. dasyurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). A white rump differentiates this gerbil from its closest relative, 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFBEBA4DFF54F998FE65ECA5" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[254,392,1646,1671]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dasyurus">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFBEBA4DFF54F998FE65ECA5" box="[254,392,1646,1671]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">G. dasyurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Belly white with a distinct line of demarcation. The skull is distinguished in that the zygomatic arches touch the auditory meatus and with well inflated bullae (
<figureCitation id="D3BA2A58FFBEBA4DFBA2F965FB93EC89" box="[1032,1150,1682,1707]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="45.[151,250,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,961,1989]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[264,1323,961,1989]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 51. A. Dorsal,B. Ventral, C. Lateral views for the skull, and D. Upper maxillary teeth for Gerbillus nanus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202877/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Figure 51</figureCitation>
). Another distinguishing character is that the base of hairs above the tail are white. Dentition indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFBEBA4DFB36F940FAF9ECED" box="[1180,1300,1718,1743]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="henleyii">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFBEBA4DFB36F940FAF9ECED" box="[1180,1300,1718,1743]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">G. henleyii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except it is larger (
<bibRefCitation id="2F104B2CFFBEBA4DFF4CF92DFDE2ECD0" box="[230,527,1754,1779]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" refId="ref30180" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 a) A morphometric and taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbillus in Jordan with notes on its current distribution. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 53, 177 - 204." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
